These articles are of the greatest importance to the Irish provision trade, to every branch of the fishery, to British navigation, commerce and manufactures in general, and particularly to the profitable management of West-India estates. Lord Sheffield is of opinion, that
most of them may be imported from Canada and Nova-Scotia, on as good, if not better terms, than from these states;
and that Nova-Scotia will, at least for some time, have little else to depend on, but her fisheries, provisions and cutting of lumber. But the experience of 1790, seven years after those provinces began to regain order, instructs us, that there were shipped in that year, from the United States to Nova-Scotia alone, 540,000 of staves and heading, 924,980 feet of boards, 285,000 shingles, and 16,000 hoops.
